ma|first1=Omkar|display-authors=etal|title=Ptychodus decurrens Agassiz (Elasmobranchii: Ptychodontidae) from the Upper Cretaceous of India|journal=Cretaceous Research|date=February 1, 2012|volume=33|issue=1|pages=183\u2013188|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2011.09.014}}</ref> The very first remains of ''Ptychodus'' were found in England in the early 19th century and was characterized as \"palates of fish\".<ref name=O&K2>{{cite web|last1=Everhard|first1=Mike|title=Ptychodontid Sharks: Late Cretaceous Shell Crushers|url=http://oceansofkansas.com/ptychodus2.html|website=Ocean of Kansas}}</ref>\nThe first discovery of Ptychodus teeth in Kansas came in 1868 when Leidy reported and described a damaged tooth near Fort Hays, Kansas.<ref name=Everhard&Cag/> After, many more teeth were uncovered in almost perfect conditions and other species within the genus were identified.<ref name=Everhard&Cag/> Fossils of species within this genus have been found in the marine strata of United States, Brazil, Canada, the Czech Republic, France, Germany, India, Japan, Jordan, Mexico, Sweden and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"PBDB\" /> The fact that so many fossils of ''Ptychodus'' have been found in different regions of the world provides evidence of a distribution of species during the Albian-Turonian time.<ref name=omkar/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Ptychodus mortoni by teratophoneus-d8torjk.png|thumb|Size of Ptychodus vs an average sized human]]\n''Ptychodus'' was about {{convert|10|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}} long and was unearthed in [[Kansas]], United States.<ref>\"BBC - Earth News - Giant predatory shark fossil unearthed in Kansas\"</ref> It was covered in [[placoid scales]] like other members of [[Hybodontoidea]], reinforced with a large cartilaginous skeleton, and was a bearer of large serrated spines along the dorsal fin.<ref name=\"oceansofkansas.com\">[http://oceansofkansas.com/FieldGuide3.html A Field Guide to Fossils of the Smoky Hill Chalk]</ref>  Unlike the colossal nektonic planktivores ''[[Rhincodon]]'' (whale sharks) and ''[[Cetorhinus]]'' (basking sharks) which relied upon gill rakers to acquire their food, the ''Ptychodus'' had a massive arrangement crushing plate teeth. A ''Ptychodus'' jaw contains many teeth, up to 550 teeth, 220 of which are on the lower jaw and 260 in the upper jaw. These teeth were very large as well. Paleontologists believe that the largest tooth plate measured 55 centimeters in length and 45 centimeters in width. There are two distinct formations of tooth plate between the genus; one being juxtaposed, non-overlapping tooth rows and another being imbricated tooth rows.<ref name=shim>{{cite journal|last1=Shimada|first1=Kenshu|title=Dentition of Late Cretaceous shark, Ptychodus mortoni (Elasmobranchii, Ptychodontidae)|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|date=October 31, 2012|volume=32|issue=6|pages=1271\u20131284|doi=10.1080/02724634.2012.707997}}</ref> It is believed that the shape coincides with the diet of the species and their geographic locations, but the time it lived has a big part as well. ''Ptychodus marginalis'' teeth differ from ''Ptychodus polygyrus''. ''P marginalis'' was in the Middle Cenomanian to Middle Turonian deposits in the English Chalk, while ''P. polygyrus'' were in the Late Santonian-Early Campanian deposits.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hamm|first1=Shawn|title=The Late Cretaceous shark Ptychodus marginalis in the Western Interior Seaway, USA|journal=Journal of Paleontology|date=May 2010|volume=84|issue=3|pages=538\u2013548|doi=10.1666/09-154.1}}</ref>\n\n==Paleobiology==\nWhile there is no solid evidence of members of the ''Ptychodus'' species living among other [[durophagous]] sharks like members of [[Heterodontidae]] (bullhead sharks), it is believed that this [[Cretaceous]] macropredator was the precursor to crushing plate teeth seen in many similar sharks and rays.<ref>Shawn A. Hamm [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/40588255?uid=3739920&uid=2129&uid=2&uid=70&uid=4&uid=3739256&sid=21104670914813 The Late Cretaceous shark, Ptychodus rugosus, (Ptychodontidae) in the Western Interior Sea] Transactions of the Kansas Academy of Science (1903) - Vol. 113, No. 1/2 (Spring 2010), pp. 44-55</ref> ''Ptychodus'' would have been a benthic predator, straying from the upper layers of the oceans that would have been inhabited by [[mosasaur]]s, [[pliosaur]]s, and other sharks such as ''[[Cretoxyrhina]]'', which it was ill-equipped to tackle or compete with. It was capable of growing to enormous size because of this, decreasing the contact it had with macropredatory organisms, and securing a vast food source with little to no competition.\nIts biological range was linked to the [[Western Interior Seaway]], where it was restricted to the middle and southern end, away from the highly concentrated remains of ''[[Cretoxyrhina]]'' and ''[[Squalicorax]]'' in the same period. It is believed that ''Ptychodus'' species not only preferred this area because of the subtropical environment, but due to the higher concentration of their prey source ''[[Cremnoceramus]]'', ''[[Volviceramus]]'' and other members of the inoceramids.<ref>Shawn Hamm [http://www.elasmo.com/refs/pdf/hamm2008-ptychodusMS.pdf Ptychodus and species 2011 - SYSTEMATIC, STRATIGRAPHIC, GEOGRAPHIC AND PALEOECOLOGICAL DISTRIBUTION OF THE LATE CRETACEOUS SHARK GENUS PTYCHODUS WITHIN THE WESTERN INTERIOR SEAWAY]</ref>\n\n===Diet===\n''Ptychodus'' was a [[molluscivore]] predator that dined upon the extremely large bivalves and crustaceans inhabiting the [[Western Interior Seaway]]. The ''Ptychodus'' diet was probably restricted to slow-moving or sessile shellfish, mollusks, invertebrates, larvae, and the occasional sunken carrion of [[Cretaceous]] megafauna that it could manipulate into its mouth. ''P. decurrens'' (found in southern India) ate animals with hard shells.<ref name=omkar/> One of the largest bivalves at the time was the 9-foot ''[[Platyceramus]]'', a shelled mollusk that would have provided a difficult meal for any other creature, but with its crushing palate ''Ptychodus'' could have broken through this durable mollusk with ease.<ref name=\"oceansofkansas.com\"/> Giant ammonites such as the ''[[Parapuzosia seppenradensis]]'', members of the [[Belemnite]] family, squid, and a variety of [[Cretaceous]] crustaceans would also make up the majority of the shark's food.\n\n==Species==\nThere have been 23 species within this genus that have been discovered so far and they include:<ref name=\"PBDB\"/>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*''Ptychodus altior'' <small> Agassiz 1839 </small>\n*''Ptychodus anonymus'' <small>Williston 1900 </small>\n*''Ptychodus arcuatus''<small> Agassiz 1837 </small>\n*''Ptychodus articulatus'' <small>Agassiz 1837</small>\n*Ptychodus atcoensis <small>Carrillo-Briceno 2013\n<small>\n*''Ptychodus belluccii'' <small>Bonarelli 1899</small>\n*''Ptychodus concentricus'' <small>Agassiz 1839</small>\n*''Ptychodus decurrens'' <small>Agassiz 1839</small>\n*''Ptychodus elevatus'' <small>Leriche 1929</small>\n*''Ptychodus gibberulus'' <small>Agassiz 1837 </small>\n*''Ptychodus janewayii'' <small>Cope 1874 </small>\n*''Ptychodus latissimus'' <small>Agassiz 1843</small>\n*''Ptychodus mahakalensis'' <small>Chiplonkar and Ghare 1977</small>\n*''Ptychodus mammillaris'' <small>Agassiz 1839</small>\n*''Ptychodus marginalis'' <small>Agassiz 1839</small>\n*''[[Ptychodus mortoni]]''<small> Agassiz 1843</small>\n*''Ptychodus multistriatus'' <small>Woodward 1889</small>\n*''Ptychodus oweni'' Dixon <small>1850</small>\n*''Ptychodus paucisulcatus'' <small>Dixon 1850</small>\n*''Ptychodus polygyrus'' <small>Agassiz 1839</small>\n*''Ptychodus rugosus'' <small>Dixon 1850</small>\n*''Ptychodus spectabili'' <small>Agassiz 1837</small>\n*''Ptychodus whipplei'' <small>Marcou 1858</small>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Ptychodus mammillaris.JPG|''Ptychodus mammillaris'' teeth\nFile:Ptychodontidae - Ptychodus decurrens.JPG|Teeth of ''Ptychodus decurrens'' from Cretaceous of United States\nFile:Ptychodontidae - Ptychodus anonymus.JPG|Teeth of ''Ptychodus anonymous'' from Cretaceous of United States\nFile:Ptychodus latissimus 1550.JPG|Teeth of ''Ptychodus'' species\nFile:PtychodusLowerJaw.jpg|The Lower Jaw of the Ptychodus\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Williston, Samuel (1900) ''University Geological Survey of Kansas, Volume VI: Paleontology part II, (Carboniferous invertebrates and Cretaceous fish)''\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Sharks|Palaeontology}}\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Ptychodus}}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/earth/hi/earth_news/newsid_8530000/8530995.stm BBC page on ''Ptychodus mortoni'': \"Giant predatory shark fossil unearthed in Kansas\"]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q648806}}\n\n[[Category:Hybodontiformes]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric shark genera]]\n[[Category:Cretaceous sharks]]\n[[Category:Paleocene sharks]]\n[[Category:Extinct animals of North America]]\n[[Category:Pridoli first appearances]]\n[[Category:Extant Silurian first appearances]]\n[[Category:Elasmobranchii|*]]\n[[Category:Wenlock first appearances]]\n[[Category:Vertebrate subclasses]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Charles Lucien Bonaparte]]\n[[Category:Mooreville Chalk]]\n", "name_user": "Anomalocaris", "label": "safe", "comment": "<small>...<small> \u2192 <small>...</small>, which can't wrap newlines", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ptychodus"}
{"title_page": "Megalocnidae", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil_range|Early Miocene|Holocene|earliest=Early Oligocene}}\n| image = Megalocnus_rodens.JPG\n| image_caption = ''[[Megalocnus|Megalocnus rodens]]'', an extinct megalocnid sloth from Cuba\n| taxon = Megalocnidae\n| authority = Presslee et al, 2019 (as family)\n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = *\u2020''[[Acratocnus]]\n*\u2020''[[Parocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Neocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Megalocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Imagocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Paulocnus]]''?\n}}\n'''Megalocnidae''' is an extinct family of [[sloth]]s, known from the [[Greater Antilles]] from the [[Early Miocene]] to the Mid-[[Holocene]]. They are known from [[Cuba]], [[Hispaniola]] and [[Puerto Rico]], but are absent from [[Jamaica]]. While they were formerly placed in the [[Megalonychidae]] alongside ground sloths like ''[[Megalonyx]]'' and [[Two-toed sloth|two-toed sloths]], recent Mitochondrial DNA and collagen studies have placed them as basal to all other sloths.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Delsuc|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last2=Kuch|first2=Melanie|last3=Gibb|first3=Gillian C.|last4=Karpinski|first4=Emil|last5=Hackenberger|first5=Dirk|last6=Szpak|first6=Paul|last7=Mart\u00ednez|first7=Jorge G.|last8=Mead|first8=Jim I.|last9=McDonald|first9=H. Gregory|last10=MacPhee|first10=Ross D.E.|last11=Billet|first11=Guillaume|date= June 2019|title=Ancient Mitogenomes Reveal the Evolutionary History and Biogeography of Sloths|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S096098221930613X|journal=Current Biology|language=en|volume=29|issue=12|pages=2031\u20132042.e6|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2019.05.043}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Presslee|first=Samantha|last2=Slater|first2=Graham J.|last3=Pujos|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|last4=Forasiepi|first4=Anal\u00eda M.|last5=Fischer|first5=Roman|last6=Molloy|first6=Kelly|last7=Mackie|first7=Meaghan|last8=Olsen|first8=Jesper V.|last9=Kramarz|first9=Alejandro|last10=Taglioretti|first10=Mat\u00edas|last11=Scaglia|first11=Fernando|date= July 2019|title=Palaeoproteomics resolves sloth relationships|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/s41559-019-0909-z|journal=Nature Ecology & Evolution|language=en|volume=3|issue=7|pages=1121\u20131130|doi=10.1038/s41559-019-0909-z|issn=2397-334X}}</ref> They displayed significant diversity in body size and lifestyle, with ''[[Megalocnus]]'' being terrestrial and probably weighing several hundred kilograms, while ''[[Neocnus]]'' was likely arboreal and weighing similar to extant tree sloths, at less than 10 kilograms.\n\n== Origin ==\nIt is thought that sloths arrived in the Caribbean at the [[Eocene-Oligocene boundary]] around 33 ma, during which there was a significant sea level drop caused by a glaciation episode.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Houben|first=Alexander J.P.|last2=van Mourik|first2=Caroline A.|last3=Montanari|first3=Alessandro|last4=Coccioni|first4=Rodolfo|last5=Brinkhuis|first5=Henk|date= June 2012|title=The Eocene\u2013Oligocene transition: Changes in sea level, temperature or both?|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0031018211001805|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=335-336|pages=75\u201383|doi=10.1016/j.palaeo.2011.04.008}}</ref> This has been associated with the GAARlandia (Greater Aves Antilles Ridge) hypothesis, where the [[Aves Ridge]] was formed a [[land bridge]] during the interval, allowing overland migration into the Greater Antilles. The existence of GAARlandia has been questioned because of the lack of geological evidence for the Aves Ridge having been subaerially exposed<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ali|first=Jason R.|date= March 2012|title=Colonizing the Caribbean: is the GAARlandia land-bridge hypothesis gaining a foothold?: Commentary|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/j.1365-2699.2011.02674.x|journal=Journal of Biogeography|language=en|volume=39|issue=3|pages=431\u2013433|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2699.2011.02674.x}}</ref> as well as the fact that many other South American animals (such as [[Ameridelphia|marsupial]]s and [[Meridiungulata|ungulates]]) are absent from the West Indies, making a land bridge unlikely.<ref>{{Citation|last=Defler|first=Thomas|title=Mammalian Invasion of the Caribbean Islands|date=2019|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/978-3-319-98449-0_11|work=History of Terrestrial Mammals in South America|volume=42|pages=221\u2013234|publisher=Springer International Publishing|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-98449-0_11|isbn=978-3-319-98448-3|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The earliest possible evidence for the presence of sloths in the Caribbean is a partial femur from the Early Oligocene of [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>MacPhee, R.D.E., and Iturralde-Vinent, M.A. (1995). [http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/handle/2246/3657 Origin of the Greater Antillean land mammal fauna, 1: New Tertiary fossils from Cuba and Puerto Rico]. Am. Mus. Novit. ''3141'', 1\u201331</ref> More definitve remains are known in form of the Early Miocene ''[[Imagocnus]]'' from [[Cuba]].\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe taxonomy for Caribbean sloths is in flux, with how many species present among the Pleistocene-Holocene taxa in question, with some species likely being junior synonyms, while the diversity of some genera is likely to be understated.<ref name=\":0\" /> The mitochondrial DNA study suggests that ''Aratocnus ye'' and ''Parocnus serus'' are deeply divergent from each other, having split during the Oligocene, suggesting an early radiation within the group.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBased on White and MacPhee (2001)<ref name=\"White2001\">{{cite book|editor1= Woods, C.A.|editor2= Sergile, F.E.|last1= White|first1= J.L.|last2= MacPhee|first2= R.D.E.|title= Biogeography of the West Indies|chapter=The Sloths of the West Indies: A Systematic and Phylogenetic Review|year= 2001|pages= 201\u2013236|publisher= CRC Press|doi= 10.1201/9781420039481-14}}</ref>\n\n*''[[Megalocnus]]'' \n**\u2020''M. rodens'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba.\n**''M. zile'' junior synonym of ''[[Parocnus|Parocnus serus]]''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=McAfee|first=Robert K.|last2=Beery|first2=Sophia M.|date=2019-06-04|title=Intraspecific variation of Megalonychid sloths from Hispaniola and the taxonomic implications|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/08912963.2019.1618294|journal=Historical Biology|language=en|pages=1\u201316|doi=10.1080/08912963.2019.1618294|issn=0891-2963}}</ref>\n*''[[Acratocnus]]'' \n** \u2020''A. odontrigonus'' Pleistocene of Puerto Rico\n** \u2020''A. ye''  Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n** \u2020''A. antillensis'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n*''[[Parocnus]]''\n** \u2020''Parocnus browni'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n** \u2020''Parocnus serus'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n*''[[Neocnus]]''\n**\u2020''N. gliriformis'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n**\u2020''N. major'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n** \u2020''N. comes'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n** \u2020''N. dousman'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n** \u2020''N. toupiti'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n*''[[Imagocnus]]'' \n**''I. zazae'' Early Miocene of Cuba\n\n''[[Paulocnus]]'' from [[Pliocene]] - [[Early Pleistocene]] deposits in [[Cura\u00e7ao]] has been suggested to be part of [[Megalonychidae]] while [[Megalocnidae]] was considered part of the group, its location close to mainland South America and considerable displacement from the Greater Antilles make referral to Megalocnidae questionable.\n\nFor other sloth taxa of the Caribbean see [[Pilosans of the Caribbean]].\n\n== Extinction ==\nSloths in the Caribbean survived much longer than ground sloths on the mainland. On Cuba the latest date for ''[[Megalocnus]]'' is calibrated 4700 BP.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MacPhee|first=R. D. E.|last2=Iturralde-Vinent|first2=M. A.|last3=V\u00e1zquez|first3=Osvaldo Jim\u00e9nez|date= January 2007|title=Prehistoric Sloth Extinctions in Cuba: Implications of a New \u201cLast\u201d Appearance Date|url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/10.18475/cjos.v43i1.a9|journal=Caribbean Journal of Science|language=en|volume=43|issue=1|pages=94\u201398|doi=10.18475/cjos.v43i1.a9|issn=0008-6452}}</ref> while dates for ''[[Parocnus|Parocnus browni]]'' are around 6250 BP. On Hispaniola the dates for some indeterminate sloth specimens are around 5000 BP, these dates roughly co-incide with the first settlement of the Caribbean, which suggests that Humans were the cause of the extinction.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steadman|first=D. W.|last2=Martin|first2=P. S.|last3=MacPhee|first3=R. D. E.|last4=Jull|first4=A. J. T.|last5=McDonald|first5=H. G.|last6=Woods|first6=C. A.|last7=Iturralde-Vinent|first7=M.|last8=Hodgins|first8=G. W. L.|date=2005-08-16|title=Asynchronous extinction of late Quaternary sloths on continents and islands|url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.0502777102|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=102|issue=33|pages=11763\u201311768|doi=10.1073/pnas.0502777102|issn=0027-8424|pmc=PMC1187974|pmid=16085711}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric mammal families]]\n[[Category:Pilosans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil_range|Early Miocene|Holocene|earliest=Early Oligocene}}\n| image = Megalocnus_rodens.JPG\n| image_caption = ''[[Megalocnus|Megalocnus rodens]]'', an extinct Megalocnid sloth from Cuba\n| taxon = Megalocnidae\n| authority = Presslee et al, 2019 (as family)\n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = *\u2020''[[Acratocnus]]\n*\u2020''[[Parocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Neocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Megalocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Imagocnus]]''\n*\u2020''[[Paulocnus]]''?\n}}\n'''Megalocnidae''' is an extinct family of [[sloth]]s, known from the [[Greater Antilles]] from the [[Early Miocene]] to the Mid-[[Holocene]]. They are known from [[Cuba]], [[Hispaniola]] and [[Puerto Rico]], but are absent from [[Jamaica]]. While they were formerly placed in the [[Megalonychidae]] alongside ground sloths li