first3=Alessandro|last4=Coccioni|first4=Rodolfo|last5=Brinkhuis|first5=Henk|date= June 2012|title=The Eocene\u2013Oligocene transition: Changes in sea level, temperature or both?|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0031018211001805|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=335-336|pages=75\u201383|doi=10.1016/j.palaeo.2011.04.008}}</ref> This has been associated with the GAARlandia (Greater Aves Antilles Ridge) hypothesis, where the [[Aves Ridge]] was formed a [[land bridge]] during the interval, allowing overland migration into the Greater Antilles. The existence of GAARlandia has been questioned because of the lack of geological evidence for the Aves Ridge having been subaerially exposed<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ali|first=Jason R.|date= March 2012|title=Colonizing the Caribbean: is the GAARlandia land-bridge hypothesis gaining a foothold?: Commentary|url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/j.1365-2699.2011.02674.x|journal=Journal of Biogeography|language=en|volume=39|issue=3|pages=431\u2013433|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2699.2011.02674.x}}</ref> as well as the fact that many other South American animals (such as [[Ameridelphia|marsupial]]s and [[Meridiungulata|ungulates]]) are absent from the West Indies, making a land bridge unlikely.<ref>{{Citation|last=Defler|first=Thomas|title=Mammalian Invasion of the Caribbean Islands|date=2019|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/978-3-319-98449-0_11|work=History of Terrestrial Mammals in South America|volume=42|pages=221\u2013234|publisher=Springer International Publishing|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-98449-0_11|isbn=978-3-319-98448-3|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The earliest possible evidence for the presence of sloths in the Caribbean is a partial femur from the Early Oligocene of [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>MacPhee, R.D.E., and Iturralde-Vinent, M.A. (1995). [http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/handle/2246/3657 Origin of the Greater Antillean land mammal fauna, 1: New Tertiary fossils from Cuba and Puerto Rico]. Am. Mus. Novit. ''3141'', 1\u201331</ref> More definitve remains are known in form of the Early Miocene ''[[Imagocnus]]'' from [[Cuba]].\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe taxonomy for Caribbean sloths is in flux, with how many species present among the Pleistocene-Holocene taxa in question, with some species likely being junior synonyms, while the diversity of some genera is likely to be understated.<ref name=\":0\" /> The mitochondrial DNA study suggests that ''Aratocnus ye'' and ''Parocnus serus'' are deeply divergent from each other, having split during the Oligocene, suggesting an early radiation within the group.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBased on White and MacPhee (2001)<ref name=\"White2001\">{{cite book|editor1= Woods, C.A.|editor2= Sergile, F.E.|last1= White|first1= J.L.|last2= MacPhee|first2= R.D.E.|title= Biogeography of the West Indies|chapter=The Sloths of the West Indies: A Systematic and Phylogenetic Review|year= 2001|pages= 201\u2013236|publisher= CRC Press|doi= 10.1201/9781420039481-14}}</ref>\n\n*''[[Megalocnus]]'' \n**\u2020''M. rodens'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba.\n**''M. zile'' junior synonym of ''[[Parocnus|Parocnus serus]]''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=McAfee|first=Robert K.|last2=Beery|first2=Sophia M.|date=2019-06-04|title=Intraspecific variation of Megalonychid sloths from Hispaniola and the taxonomic implications|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/08912963.2019.1618294|journal=Historical Biology|language=en|pages=1\u201316|doi=10.1080/08912963.2019.1618294|issn=0891-2963}}</ref>\n*''[[Acratocnus]]'' \n** \u2020''A. odontrigonus'' Pleistocene of Puerto Rico\n** \u2020''A. ye''  Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n** \u2020''A. antillensis'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n*''[[Parocnus]]''\n** \u2020''Parocnus browni'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n** \u2020''Parocnus serus'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n*''[[Neocnus]]''\n**\u2020''N. gliriformis'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n**\u2020''N. major'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Cuba\n** \u2020''N. comes'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n** \u2020''N. dousman'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n** \u2020''N. toupiti'' Pleistocene to Holocene of Hispaniola\n*''[[Imagocnus]]'' \n**''I. zazae'' Early Miocene of Cuba\n\n''[[Paulocnus]]'' from [[Pliocene]] - [[Early Pleistocene]] deposits in [[Cura\u00e7ao]] has been suggested to be part of [[Megalonychidae]] while [[Megalocnidae]] was considered part of the group, its location close to mainland South America and considerable displacement from the Greater Antilles make referral to Megalocnidae questionable.\n\nFor other sloth taxa of the Caribbean see [[Pilosans of the Caribbean]].\n\n== Extinction ==\nSloths in the Caribbean survived much longer than ground sloths on the mainland. On Cuba the latest date for ''[[Megalocnus]]'' is calibrated 4700 BP.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MacPhee|first=R. D. E.|last2=Iturralde-Vinent|first2=M. A.|last3=V\u00e1zquez|first3=Osvaldo Jim\u00e9nez|date= January 2007|title=Prehistoric Sloth Extinctions in Cuba: Implications of a New \u201cLast\u201d Appearance Date|url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/10.18475/cjos.v43i1.a9|journal=Caribbean Journal of Science|language=en|volume=43|issue=1|pages=94\u201398|doi=10.18475/cjos.v43i1.a9|issn=0008-6452}}</ref> while dates for ''[[Parocnus|Parocnus browni]]'' are around 6250 BP. On Hispaniola the dates for some indeterminate sloth specimens are around 5000 BP, these dates roughly co-incide with the first settlement of the Caribbean, which suggests that Humans were the cause of the extinction.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steadman|first=D. W.|last2=Martin|first2=P. S.|last3=MacPhee|first3=R. D. E.|last4=Jull|first4=A. J. T.|last5=McDonald|first5=H. G.|last6=Woods|first6=C. A.|last7=Iturralde-Vinent|first7=M.|last8=Hodgins|first8=G. W. L.|date=2005-08-16|title=Asynchronous extinction of late Quaternary sloths on continents and islands|url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.0502777102|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=102|issue=33|pages=11763\u201311768|doi=10.1073/pnas.0502777102|issn=0027-8424|pmc=PMC1187974|pmid=16085711}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric mammal families]]\n[[Category:Pilosans]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "-> lower case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Megalocnidae"}
